{
  "response": "# Rich Text Editor Formatting Toolbar Accessibility Design Plan\n\n> **For Claude:** Use a11y-planner protocol. Review with a11y-critic after implementation.  \n> **Compliance target:** WCAG 2.2 AA  \n> **Users who need accessibility:** Screen reader users, keyboard-only users, low vision users, users with motor impairments  \n> **Assistive technologies:** NVDA, JAWS, VoiceOver, keyboard-only navigation  \n\n**Feature:** A rich text editor formatting toolbar with 24 buttons organized into 4 labeled groups, implemented as one tab stop with roving tabindex and arrow-key navigation.  \n**Risk Level:** Medium-high  \n**Component/Page Type:** Composite toolbar widget with toggle buttons and dialog-opening action buttons  \n\n---\n\n## Scope & Context\n\nThe current toolbar has 24 independent `<button>` elements in the page tab order. That creates a keyboard burden: users must press Tab 24 times to move past the editor toolbar. The redesigned toolbar must behave as one composite widget: Tab enters the toolbar once, arrow keys move between toolbar buttons, and Tab exits the toolbar to the next logical page element.\n\nThe core design decision is whether this is a toolbar or a menubar. The correct pattern is **WAI-ARIA APG Toolbar**, not Menubar.\n\nThe design mockup label \u201cFormat Menu\u201d does not determine the accessibility role. Roles describe interaction contracts, not visual labels or product language. A menubar implies menu semantics and submenu behavior: top-level menu items, menuitem roles, Down Arrow opening menus, Escape closing menus, and menu-like command structures. This component is a flat group of editor commands with no submenus. Using `role=\"menubar\"` would create false expectations for screen reader and keyboard users.\n\n**Decision:** Use `role=\"toolbar\"` with grouped native buttons.\n\n**Primary APG pattern:**  \nWAI-ARIA APG Toolbar Pattern: https://www.w3.org/WAI/ARIA/apg/patterns/toolbar/\n\n**Secondary APG pattern for dialogs opened by toolbar buttons:**  \nWAI-ARIA APG Modal Dialog Pattern: https://www.w3.org/WAI/ARIA/apg/patterns/dialog-modal/\n\nThis plan does not claim that every rich text editor command must remain visible in one toolbar forever. It only covers the specified flat 24-button toolbar. If future work adds dropdowns, split buttons, nested choices, color pickers, or command menus, those controls need separate APG pattern decisions.\n\n---\n\n## Semantic Structure Plan\n\nThe toolbar should sit between the editable document body and adjacent editor UI, such as sidebars. It should have a clear accessible name and internal groups so screen reader users can understand the command organization.\n\nUse native `<button>` elements for all toolbar commands. Do not replace them with `div role=\"button\"` unless there is an unavoidable technical constraint.\n\n### Structure Diagram\n\n```html\n<main id=\"main-content\">\n  <section aria-labelledby=\"editor-heading\">\n    <h1 id=\"editor-heading\">Document editor</h1>\n\n    <div id=\"editor-body\">\n      Editable document body\n    </div>\n\n    <div\n      role=\"toolbar\"\n      aria-label=\"Formatting toolbar\"\n      aria-controls=\"editor-body\"\n    >\n      <div role=\"group\" aria-label=\"Text style\">\n        <button type=\"button\" aria-label=\"Bold\" aria-pressed=\"false\" tabindex=\"0\">B</button>\n        <button type=\"button\" aria-label=\"Italic\" aria-pressed=\"false\" tabindex=\"-1\">I</button>\n        <button type=\"button\" aria-label=\"Underline\" aria-pressed=\"false\" tabindex=\"-1\">U</button>\n      </div>\n\n      <div role=\"group\" aria-label=\"Alignment\">\n        <button type=\"button\" aria-label=\"Align left\" tabindex=\"-1\">...</button>\n      </div>\n\n      <div role=\"group\" aria-label=\"Lists\">\n        <button type=\"button\" aria-label=\"Bulleted list\" tabindex=\"-1\">...</button>\n      </div>\n\n      <div role=\"group\" aria-label=\"Insert\">\n        <button type=\"button\" aria-label=\"Insert link\" tabindex=\"-1\">...</button>\n        <button type=\"button\" aria-label=\"Insert image\" tabindex=\"-1\">...</button>\n      </div>\n    </div>\n\n    <aside aria-label=\"Editor sidebar\">\n      Sidebar tools\n    </aside>\n  </section>\n</main>\n```\n\n### Semantic Decisions\n\nThe toolbar container uses `role=\"toolbar\"` and `aria-label=\"Formatting toolbar\"` to expose the composite control name. This satisfies WCAG 4.1.2 Name, Role, Value.\n\nThe toolbar name should be \u201cFormatting toolbar,\u201d not \u201cFormat Menu.\u201d \u201cMenu\u201d would imply the wrong interaction model. Visible UI copy can say \u201cFormat\u201d if desired, but the accessible name should identify the control as a toolbar.\n\nEach group uses `role=\"group\"` with `aria-label` for orientation: \u201cText style,\u201d \u201cAlignment,\u201d \u201cLists,\u201d and \u201cInsert.\u201d This satisfies WCAG 1.3.1 Info and Relationships and WCAG 4.1.2 Name, Role, Value.\n\nEach command remains a native `<button>`, satisfying WCAG 2.1.1 Keyboard and WCAG 4.1.2 Name, Role, Value through built-in button semantics.\n\nVisual symbols such as B, I, U, alignment icons, list icons, link icons, or image icons must not be the only accessible name unless they are understandable as text. Icon-only buttons need `aria-label`. Decorative icon glyphs inside buttons should be `aria-hidden=\"true\"` when the parent button has a proper accessible name. This satisfies WCAG 1.1.1 Non-text Content and WCAG 4.1.2 Name, Role, Value.\n\n---\n\n## Interaction Pattern Design\n\n### Pattern Decision\n\n| Candidate Role | Decision | Reason |\n|---|---:|---|\n| `role=\"toolbar\"` | Use | Correct APG pattern for a flat collection of command buttons. Supports roving tabindex and arrow-key navigation. |\n| `role=\"menubar\"` | Do not use | Menubar implies menuitem semantics, submenu behavior, and Down Arrow menu opening. This component has no submenus. |\n| Plain group of buttons | Do not use | Would keep 24 buttons in tab order or require ad hoc keyboard behavior without a composite widget contract. |\n\n### Interactive Elements Table\n\n| Widget | APG Pattern | Keyboard Model | ARIA Attributes | WCAG Citation |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| Toolbar container | [APG Toolbar](https://www.w3.org/WAI/ARIA/apg/patterns/toolbar/) | Tab enters toolbar at active roving item; Tab exits toolbar | `role=\"toolbar\"`, `aria-label=\"Formatting toolbar\"`, optional `aria-controls=\"editor-body\"` | 2.1.1 Keyboard, 2.4.3 Focus Order, 4.1.2 Name Role Value |\n| Toolbar groups | [APG Toolbar](https://www.w3.org/WAI/ARIA/apg/patterns/toolbar/) with grouped controls | Arrow navigation passes through grouped buttons in DOM order | `role=\"group\"`, `aria-label=\"Text style\"` etc. | 1.3.1 Info and Relationships, 4.1.2 Name Role Value |\n| Toggle buttons: Bold, Italic, Underline | [APG Button, Toggle Button](https://www.w3.org/WAI/ARIA/apg/patterns/button/) inside toolbar | Enter/Space toggles pressed state; arrows move focus | `aria-pressed=\"true\"` or `\"false\"` | 2.1.1 Keyboard, 4.1.2 Name Role Value |\n| Action buttons: Insert Link, Insert Image | [APG Button](https://www.w3.org/WAI/ARIA/apg/patterns/button/) inside toolbar | Enter/Space activates command or opens dialog; arrows move focus | No `aria-pressed`; add `aria-haspopup=\"dialog\"` only for buttons that open dialogs | 2.1.1 Keyboard, 4.1.2 Name Role Value |\n| Insert dialogs | [APG Modal Dialog](https://www.w3.org/WAI/ARIA/apg/patterns/dialog-modal/) | Tab trapped inside dialog; Escape closes; close restores focus | `role=\"dialog\"`, `aria-modal=\"true\"`, `aria-labelledby`, optional `aria-describedby` | 2.1.1 Keyboard, 2.1.2 No Keyboard Trap, 2.4.3 Focus Order, 4.1.2 Name Role Value |\n\n### Keyboard Model\n\n**Tab**\n- From editor body: moves focus to the toolbar\u2019s current roving button.\n- From inside toolbar: exits the toolbar to the next logical focus target, such as the editor sidebar.\n- Shift+Tab from inside toolbar: exits to the previous logical focus target, such as the editor body or prior editor control.\n\n**Left Arrow / Right Arrow**\n- Move focus through every enabled toolbar button in DOM order.\n- Navigation wraps at edges.\n- Right Arrow on the last button moves to the first button.\n- Left Arrow on the first button moves to the last button.\n- After movement, the newly focused button receives `tabindex=\"0\"` and the previously focused button receives `tabindex=\"-1\"`.\n\n**Home / End**\n- Home moves focus to the first enabled toolbar button.\n- End moves focus to the last enabled toolbar button.\n- Though optional in APG Toolbar, include these because the toolbar has 24 commands and power users expect fast edge navigation.\n\n**Enter / Space**\n- On toggle buttons: toggles the command state and updates `aria-pressed`.\n- On action buttons: activates the command. If the command opens a dialog, focus moves into the dialog according to the modal dialog focus plan.\n- Enter/Space must not be overloaded to move between toolbar buttons.\n\n**Escape**\n- Does not close the toolbar because the toolbar is not a popup.\n- If focus is inside a dialog opened from the toolbar, Escape closes the dialog and restores focus to the triggering toolbar button.\n\n### Group Navigation Decision\n\nUse arrow keys to step through **every button**, not jump group-to-group.\n\nReason: the toolbar is a flat command surface with 24 buttons. Skipping between groups would make some controls unreachable or require a second undocumented navigation mode. APG Toolbar allows grouping for organization, but groups do not require separate Tab stops. Keeping the entire toolbar as one Tab stop directly addresses the current defect.\n\nThis plan does not use Tab/Shift+Tab between internal groups because that would create 4 tab stops inside the toolbar instead of 1. It would partially fix the current problem but would not meet the stated requirement.\n\n---\n\n## Roving Tabindex Plan\n\nExactly one enabled toolbar button has `tabindex=\"0\"` at any time. All other enabled toolbar buttons have `tabindex=\"-1\"`.\n\nInitial default:\n- First enabled button in the toolbar gets `tabindex=\"0\"`.\n- All other enabled buttons get `tabindex=\"-1\"`.\n\nAfter arrow navigation:\n- The destination button receives DOM focus.\n- The destination button becomes `tabindex=\"0\"`.\n- The previously active button becomes `tabindex=\"-1\"`.\n\nWhen a toggle button is activated:\n- Focus remains on the button.\n- `tabindex` does not change.\n- `aria-pressed` updates.\n\nWhen an action button opens a dialog:\n- The triggering button remains the remembered roving item.\n- The triggering button should still be the toolbar item with `tabindex=\"0\"` while the dialog is open.\n- When the dialog closes, focus returns to that same button.\n\nDisabled buttons:\n- Prefer native `disabled` only if the command should be removed from keyboard focus and skipped by arrow navigation.\n- If a disabled command must remain discoverable, use `aria-disabled=\"true\"` and keep it arrow-focusable, but prevent activation. This is more complex and should be used only when discoverability is required.\n- In either case, the disabled state must be visually and programmatically communicated per WCAG 4.1.2.\n\n---\n\n## Focus Management Plan\n\n### Logical Focus Order\n\n1. Previous editor control or editable document body.\n2. Toolbar as one composite stop, landing on the active roving button.\n3. Next page element after toolbar, such as editor sidebar, metadata panel, or next landmark.\n\nThe toolbar must not expose 24 separate Tab stops. That is the existing accessibility failure.\n\n### Internal Toolbar Focus\n\nFocus moves internally only by arrow keys, Home, and End. The focus indicator must be visible on every button, including icon-only buttons and buttons inside each group.\n\nWhen focus enters the toolbar from outside:\n- If the user has not previously focused a toolbar button, focus the first enabled command.\n- If the user previously focused a command in this session, focus the last active roving command. This preserves user context and satisfies WCAG 2.4.3 Focus Order.\n\n### Dialog Focus Restoration\n\nFor buttons such as Insert Link or Insert Image:\n\n1. User focuses the toolbar button.\n2. User presses Enter or Space.\n3. Store a reference to the triggering button.\n4. Open the modal dialog.\n5. Move focus into the dialog, preferably to the dialog title if the dialog contains explanatory content, or the first input if the dialog is short and form-first.\n6. Trap Tab and Shift+Tab inside the dialog.\n7. Escape or Close closes the dialog.\n8. Return focus to the triggering toolbar button.\n9. Keep that triggering button as `tabindex=\"0\"` in the toolbar.\n\nThis satisfies WCAG 2.1.1 Keyboard, WCAG 2.1.2 No Keyboard Trap, WCAG 2.4.3 Focus Order, and APG Modal Dialog.\n\n### Focus Visibility\n\nEvery toolbar button needs a visible focus indicator with at least 3:1 contrast against adjacent colors. Use a two-color focus indicator, such as a dark outline plus light offset shadow, to remain visible across button states and themes. Use `:focus-visible` so keyboard users receive clear focus indication without adding noisy mouse-click styling.\n\nThis satisfies WCAG 2.4.7 Focus Visible and WCAG 2.4.13 Focus Appearance.\n\n---\n\n## State Communication Design\n\n### State Communication Table\n\n| State | Visual Indicator | Programmatic Indicator | ARIA Attribute | WCAG Citation |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| Toolbar focused on one command | Visible focus ring on active button | DOM focus on current button; only this button has `tabindex=\"0\"` | `tabindex=\"0\"` on active item; `tabindex=\"-1\"` on others | 2.1.1, 2.4.3, 2.4.7 |\n| Bold/Italic/Underline pressed | Active styling plus icon/text state; not color alone | Toggle state exposed to AT | `aria-pressed=\"true\"` | 4.1.2 |\n| Bold/Italic/Underline not pressed | Default styling | Toggle state exposed to AT | `aria-pressed=\"false\"` | 4.1.2 |\n| Action button available | Normal button styling | Native button semantics | No `aria-pressed` | 4.1.2 |\n| Action button opens dialog | Button label plus optional visual cue | Dialog behavior exposed | `aria-haspopup=\"dialog\"` on the opener if it opens a dialog | 4.1.2 |\n| Disabled command | Dimmed styling plus disabled cursor/icon/text treatment | Disabled state exposed | Native `disabled` or `aria-disabled=\"true\"` depending on discoverability decision | 1.4.1, 4.1.2 |\n| Dialog open | Modal visible; background visually inactive | Modal semantics and focus trap | `role=\"dialog\"`, `aria-modal=\"true\"`, `aria-labelledby` | 2.1.2, 4.1.2 |\n| Command applied to editor selection | Button state updates where persistent | For persistent toggles, `aria-pressed` reflects state | `aria-pressed` only for toggle buttons | 4.1.2 |\n| Loading/inserting media | Spinner plus status text | Status announced politely | `role=\"status\"` or `aria-live=\"polite\"` | 4.1.3 |\n\nDo not use `aria-selected` for Bold, Italic, Underline. `aria-selected` belongs to selection patterns such as tabs, options, and grid cells. These controls are toggle buttons, so `aria-pressed` is the correct state.\n\nDo not add `aria-pressed` to action buttons like Insert Link or Insert Image. They perform an action or open a dialog; they do not represent an on/off state.\n\n### Screen Reader Announcements\n\nExpected examples:\n\n- Toolbar entry: \u201cFormatting toolbar.\u201d\n- Group orientation, depending on screen reader support: \u201cText style group.\u201d\n- Toggle button focus: \u201cBold, toggle button, not pressed\u201d or \u201cBold, button, not pressed.\u201d\n- Toggle after activation: \u201cPressed\u201d or \u201cNot pressed.\u201d\n- Action button focus: \u201cInsert link, button\u201d or \u201cInsert link, button, has popup dialog\u201d if `aria-haspopup=\"dialog\"` is used.\n- Dialog open: screen reader announces dialog title and dialog role.\n- Dialog close: focus returns to \u201cInsert link, button.\u201d\n\nScreen reader group-label announcements vary by AT/browser combination, so group labels are an orientation enhancement, not the only way users should understand the toolbar. Button labels must be independently clear.\n\n---\n\n## Visual Accessibility Plan\n\nAll toolbar text and icon controls must meet WCAG 1.4.3 Contrast Minimum and WCAG 1.4.11 Non-text Contrast.\n\nRequirements:\n- Normal text: minimum 4.5:1 contrast.\n- Large text: minimum 3:1 contrast.\n- Icon strokes, button boundaries, pressed indicators, and focus rings: minimum 3:1 contrast against adjacent colors.\n- Focus indicators: visible in default, hover, pressed, disabled-adjacent, light mode, dark mode, and high contrast mode.\n- Minimum target size: at least 24x24 CSS pixels per WCAG 2.5.8; 44x44 is recommended for editor toolbars where space permits.\n- Pressed state must not rely on color alone. Use at least two indicators, such as active background plus inset border, icon treatment, or persistent pressed styling.\n- Disabled state must not rely on opacity alone if it causes contrast failure.\n- Toolbar must reflow at 200% zoom and remain usable at 400% zoom / 320 CSS pixel equivalent without horizontal page scrolling. Horizontal scrolling inside the toolbar should be avoided unless there is no feasible alternative, and if used, it needs keyboard access and visible scroll affordance.\n- Motion should be minimal. If button state transitions or dialog animations exist, respect `prefers-reduced-motion`.\n\nWCAG citations: 1.4.1 Use of Color, 1.4.3 Contrast Minimum, 1.4.10 Reflow, 1.4.11 Non-text Contrast, 2.4.7 Focus Visible, 2.4.13 Focus Appearance, 2.5.8 Target Size.\n\n---\n\n## Content Accessibility Plan\n\nToolbar and group names:\n- Toolbar accessible name: \u201cFormatting toolbar.\u201d\n- Group names: \u201cText style,\u201d \u201cAlignment,\u201d \u201cLists,\u201d \u201cInsert.\u201d\n- Avoid \u201cFormat Menu\u201d as the accessible name because it suggests menu behavior.\n\nButton names:\n- Every button needs a clear accessible name.\n- Icon-only buttons must use `aria-label`.\n- Do not use `title` as the accessible name mechanism.\n- Good labels: \u201cBold,\u201d \u201cItalic,\u201d \u201cUnderline,\u201d \u201cAlign left,\u201d \u201cAlign center,\u201d \u201cBulleted list,\u201d \u201cNumbered list,\u201d \u201cInsert link,\u201d \u201cInsert image.\u201d\n- If a command opens a dialog, the label should describe the action: \u201cInsert link,\u201d not \u201cLink dialog.\u201d\n\nVisual icon handling:\n- Decorative icons inside buttons should be `aria-hidden=\"true\"` when the parent button has an accessible name.\n- If visible text like \u201cB\u201d is used, ensure the accessible label still says \u201cBold,\u201d not only \u201cB.\u201d\n\nReading order:\n- DOM order should match the visual toolbar order and arrow-key order.\n- Groups should be ordered Text Style, Alignment, Lists, Insert unless the product team changes the visible order.\n\nLanguage:\n- The page root should have the correct `lang`, such as `lang=\"en\"`, satisfying WCAG 3.1.1.\n\n---\n\n## Testing Strategy\n\n### Automated and Static Testing\n\nRun static JSX accessibility checks:\n- Invalid ARIA attributes.\n- Missing accessible names on icon buttons.\n- Inappropriate roles.\n- Buttons without type.\n- Misused `aria-selected` on buttons.\n\nRun runtime axe checks:\n- Toolbar has an accessible name.\n- Buttons have accessible names.\n- Dialogs have valid labels.\n- ARIA attributes are valid for their roles.\n- Color contrast passes.\n\nAutomated tools will not fully prove roving tabindex, keyboard wrapping, screen reader announcement quality, or focus restoration. Those require keyboard and screen reader tests.\n\n### DOM Verification Requirements\n\nVerify rendered DOM, not just component props:\n\n- Toolbar container has `role=\"toolbar\"` and `aria-label=\"Formatting toolbar\"`.\n- No toolbar container uses `role=\"menubar\"`.\n- Groups render with `role=\"group\"` and correct `aria-label`.\n- Exactly one enabled toolbar button has `tabindex=\"0\"`.\n- All other enabled toolbar buttons have `tabindex=\"-1\"`.\n- Toggle buttons have `aria-pressed`.\n- Action buttons do not have `aria-pressed`.\n- Dialog-opening buttons have correct activation behavior and optional `aria-haspopup=\"dialog\"`.\n- Dialogs render with `role=\"dialog\"`, `aria-modal=\"true\"`, and `aria-labelledby`.\n\n### Keyboard Test Cases\n\n1. **Tab enters toolbar once**\n   - Place focus in editor body.\n   - Press Tab.\n   - Expected: focus lands on first enabled toolbar button or last active roving button.\n   - Expected: only focused toolbar button has `tabindex=\"0\"`.\n\n2. **Tab exits toolbar**\n   - With focus on any toolbar button, press Tab.\n   - Expected: focus moves to the next logical control after the toolbar, not to the next toolbar button.\n\n3. **Shift+Tab exits backward**\n   - With focus on any toolbar button, press Shift+Tab.\n   - Expected: focus moves to the previous logical control before the toolbar.\n\n4. **Right Arrow navigation**\n   - Focus first toolbar button.\n   - Press Right Arrow.\n   - Expected: focus moves to the next button in DOM order.\n   - Expected: new button has `tabindex=\"0\"` and previous button has `tabindex=\"-1\"`.\n\n5. **Left Arrow navigation**\n   - Focus second toolbar button.\n   - Press Left Arrow.\n   - Expected: focus moves to previous button.\n\n6. **Wrapping**\n   - Focus last toolbar button.\n   - Press Right Arrow.\n   - Expected: focus wraps to first enabled button.\n   - Focus first toolbar button.\n   - Press Left Arrow.\n   - Expected: focus wraps to last enabled button.\n\n7. **Home / End**\n   - Focus a middle toolbar button.\n   - Press Home.\n   - Expected: focus moves to first enabled button.\n   - Press End.\n   - Expected: focus moves to last enabled button.\n\n8. **Toggle button activation**\n   - Focus Bold.\n   - Press Space.\n   - Expected: `aria-pressed` changes from `\"false\"` to `\"true\"`.\n   - Expected: focus remains on Bold.\n   - Press Space again.\n   - Expected: `aria-pressed` returns to `\"false\"`.\n\n9. **Action button activation**\n   - Focus Insert Link.\n   - Press Enter.\n   - Expected: link dialog opens.\n   - Expected: focus moves inside dialog.\n   - Expected: toolbar focus does not leak behind dialog.\n\n10. **Dialog close restoration**\n   - Open Insert Link dialog from toolbar.\n   - Press Escape.\n   - Expected: dialog closes.\n   - Expected: focus returns to Insert Link button.\n   - Expected: Insert Link has `tabindex=\"0\"`.\n\n11. **Group traversal**\n   - Arrow through last button of Text Style group.\n   - Expected: next arrow press moves to first button of Alignment group, not out of the toolbar and not to a group container.\n\n12. **Screen reader smoke test**\n   - Navigate to toolbar with NVDA, JAWS, and VoiceOver.\n   - Expected: toolbar name is announced.\n   - Expected: button name, role, and pressed state are announced.\n   - Expected: groups provide useful orientation where supported.\n\n---\n\n## Implementation Tasks\n\n### Task 1: Replace 24 Tab Stops with APG Toolbar Composite\n\n\ud83d\udd0d **Review checkpoint after this task**\n\n**Files:**\n- Toolbar component file\n- Toolbar keyboard navigation tests\n- Toolbar rendering tests\n\n**Structure Stub:**\n```html\n<div role=\"toolbar\" aria-label=\"Formatting toolbar\" aria-controls=\"editor-body\">\n  <div role=\"group\" aria-label=\"Text style\">\n    <button type=\"button\" tabindex=\"0\">...</button>\n    <button type=\"button\" tabindex=\"-1\">...</button>\n  </div>\n</div>\n```\n\n**ARIA Attributes:**\n- `role=\"toolbar\"`: exposes composite toolbar role; WCAG 4.1.2.\n- `aria-label=\"Formatting toolbar\"`: provides accessible name; WCAG 4.1.2.\n- `aria-controls=\"editor-body\"` if the toolbar controls a specific editor region; WCAG 4.1.2.\n- `role=\"group\"` and group `aria-label`: exposes command grouping; WCAG 1.3.1 and 4.1.2.\n- `tabindex=\"0\"` / `tabindex=\"-1\"`: implements roving focus; WCAG 2.1.1 and 2.4.3.\n\n**Keyboard Interactions:**\n- Tab enters toolbar once.\n- Tab exits toolbar.\n- Shift+Tab exits backward.\n- Left/Right arrows move through every enabled button.\n- Home/End move to first/last enabled button.\n\n**Tests:**\n- Exactly one toolbar button has `tabindex=\"0\"`.\n- No toolbar button except the active roving item is in the Tab order.\n- Arrow keys move focus and update tabindex.\n- Tab exits the toolbar instead of stepping through buttons.\n\n**WCAG Criteria:**\n- 2.1.1 Keyboard\n- 2.4.3 Focus Order\n- 4.1.2 Name, Role, Value\n\n**a11y-critic focus:**\n- Verify `role=\"toolbar\"` is used instead of `role=\"menubar\"`.\n- Verify roving tabindex is complete.\n- Verify the toolbar has one Tab stop.\n\n---\n\n### Task 2: Add Group Semantics and Accessible Button Names\n\n\ud83d\udd0d **Review checkpoint after this task**\n\n**Structure Stub:**\n```html\n<div role=\"group\" aria-label=\"Lists\">\n  <button type=\"button\" aria-label=\"Bulleted list\" tabindex=\"-1\">\n    <span aria-hidden=\"true\">...</span>\n  </button>\n</div>\n```\n\n**ARIA Attributes:**\n- Group `aria-label`: communicates group purpose; WCAG 1.3.1 and 4.1.2.\n- Button `aria-label` for icon-only buttons: provides accessible name; WCAG 4.1.2.\n- Icon `aria-hidden=\"true\"` when decorative; WCAG 1.1.1.\n\n**Keyboard Interactions:**\n- Arrow keys step through buttons across group boundaries.\n- Group containers are not focusable.\n\n**Tests:**\n- All 24 buttons have accessible names.\n- Group labels exist and match intended categories.\n- Arrow navigation crosses from one group to the next.\n\n**WCAG Criteria:**\n- 1.1.1 Non-text Content\n- 1.3.1 Info and Relationships\n- 4.1.2 Name, Role, Value\n\n**a11y-critic focus:**\n- Verify group labels orient users without adding extra Tab stops.\n- Verify icon-only buttons do not rely on `title`.\n\n---\n\n### Task 3: Implement Toggle and Action Button State Correctly\n\n\ud83d\udd0d **Review checkpoint after this task**\n\n**Structure Stub:**\n```html\n<button type=\"button\" aria-label=\"Bold\" aria-pressed=\"false\" tabindex=\"0\">\n  <span aria-hidden=\"true\">B</span>\n</button>\n\n<button type=\"button\" aria-label=\"Insert link\" aria-haspopup=\"dialog\" tabindex=\"-1\">\n  <span aria-hidden=\"true\">...</span>\n</button>\n```\n\n**ARIA Attributes:**\n- `aria-pressed`: only for toggle buttons; WCAG 4.1.2.\n- No `aria-selected` on toolbar buttons; selected is the wrong state.\n- No `aria-pressed` on action buttons.\n- `aria-haspopup=\"dialog\"` only for buttons that open dialogs; WCAG 4.1.2.\n\n**Keyboard Interactions:**\n- Enter/Space toggles toggle buttons.\n- Enter/Space activates action buttons.\n- Activation does not disturb roving tabindex unless a dialog opens.\n\n**Tests:**\n- Bold, Italic, Underline expose `aria-pressed`.\n- Action buttons do not expose `aria-pressed`.\n- Toggle activation updates state and keeps focus on the button.\n- Action activation opens the correct dialog or performs the command.\n\n**WCAG Criteria:**\n- 2.1.1 Keyboard\n- 4.1.2 Name, Role, Value\n\n**a11y-critic focus:**\n- Verify toggle state uses `aria-pressed`, not `aria-selected`.\n- Verify action buttons are not falsely exposed as toggles.\n\n---\n\n### Task 4: Add Dialog Focus Management for Toolbar Actions\n\n\ud83d\udd0d **Review checkpoint after this task**\n\n**Structure Stub:**\n```html\n<div role=\"dialog\" aria-modal=\"true\" aria-labelledby=\"insert-link-title\">\n  <h2 id=\"insert-link-title\">Insert link</h2>\n  ...\n</div>\n```\n\n**ARIA Attributes:**\n- `role=\"dialog\"`: exposes dialog role; WCAG 4.1.2.\n- `aria-modal=\"true\"`: communicates modal behavior; WCAG 4.1.2.\n- `aria-labelledby`: names the dialog; WCAG 4.1.2.\n- Field labels and errors inside dialogs must follow form accessibility rules; WCAG 1.3.1, 3.3.1, 3.3.2.\n\n**Keyboard Interactions:**\n- Enter/Space on Insert Link or Insert Image opens dialog.\n- Focus moves into dialog.\n- Tab and Shift+Tab are trapped inside dialog.\n- Escape closes dialog.\n- Closing restores focus to the triggering toolbar button.\n\n**Tests:**\n- Dialog opens from toolbar button.\n- Focus enters dialog.\n- Focus cannot escape modal while open.\n- Escape closes dialog.\n- Focus returns to the exact triggering button.\n- Triggering button remains the toolbar roving item.\n\n**WCAG Criteria:**\n- 2.1.1 Keyboard\n- 2.1.2 No Keyboard Trap\n- 2.4.3 Focus Order\n- 4.1.2 Name, Role, Value\n\n**a11y-critic focus:**\n- Verify focus restoration.\n- Verify toolbar roving state survives dialog open/close.\n- Verify modal semantics and focus trap.\n\n---\n\n## a11y-Critic Review Checkpoints\n\n| Checkpoint | After Task | Focus Areas |\n|---|---|---|\n| 1 | Task 1 | Toolbar vs menubar role decision, one Tab stop, roving tabindex correctness |\n| 2 | Task 2 | Group labels, accessible button names, icon hiding, no `title`-based names |\n| 3 | Task 3 | Toggle/action distinction, `aria-pressed`, no `aria-selected`, activation behavior |\n| 4 | Task 4 | Dialog semantics, focus trap, Escape behavior, focus restoration to trigger |\n\n---\n\n## Failure Modes This Plan Prevents\n\n- Using `role=\"menubar\"` because the mockup says \u201cFormat Menu.\u201d\n- Keeping all 24 buttons in the Tab order.\n- Making group containers focusable.\n- Using `aria-selected` for Bold, Italic, or Underline.\n- Adding `aria-pressed` to action buttons.\n- Losing focus after Insert Link or Insert Image dialogs close.\n- Relying on icon glyphs, `title`, or visual labels that do not become accessible names.\n- Making pressed state color-only.\n- Implementing arrow-key movement without updating roving `tabindex`.\n- Testing visuals without verifying rendered ARIA and tabindex placement.\n\n---\n\n## References\n\n- WAI-ARIA APG Toolbar Pattern: https://www.w3.org/WAI/ARIA/apg/patterns/toolbar/\n- WAI-ARIA APG Button Pattern: https://www.w3.org/WAI/ARIA/apg/patterns/button/\n- WAI-ARIA APG Modal Dialog Pattern: https://www.w3.org/WAI/ARIA/apg/patterns/dialog-modal/\n- WCAG 2.2 Quick Reference: https://www.w3.org/WAI/WCAG22/quickref/",
